Since the beginning of {{ill|rice cultivation|ja|稲作|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Japanese history, rituals to honor the {{ill|Ta-no-Kami|ja|田の神|Ta-no-Kami=Ta-no-Kami|lt=god of the rice field|qq=draft|qq=draft}} have been held throughout the country. Among them, Sumiyoshi Taisha's Otaue is believed to have originated from {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft}} establishing a rice field. This sacred event, which remains faithfully preserved today, is dedicated to {{ill|bumper crop|ja|五穀豊穣|lt=bountiful harvests|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is believed that strong spirits reside in the rice seedlings planted in the mother {{ill|Earth|ja|大地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. During the planting, music, songs, dances, and performances are offered to enhance the vitality of the grains, ensuring their rich growth and plentiful yield in the autumn.
This Otaue ritual is held annually on {{ill|June 14|ja|6月14日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. On the morning of the event, ceremonies called Powder Ceremony (粉黛式) and Sake Offering Ceremony (戴盃式) take place at the shrine's inner sanctum, where planters, {{ill|chigo|ja|稚児|chigo=chigo|lt=children attendants|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and ceremonial women (御稔女) don special attire, apply makeup, and partake in sacred sake. Following this, all participants undergo purification (修祓) at the {{ill|Stone Stage|ja|日本三舞台|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and attend a dedication ceremony at the First Shrine (第一本宮). The procession, including musicians, {{ill|yaotome|ja|八乙女|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ceremonial women, planters, substitutes, children attendants, warriors in colorful garb, and dancers of the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Odori|ja|住吉踊り|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, then heads to the rice field.
After sacred water is sprinkled around the field to purify it, rice seedlings are handed over for planting. Planting begins when seedlings are transferred from the planters to substitutes. Throughout the ritual, various performances are offered, including rice-planting dances by the yaotome, mock battles between red and white teams of warriors using bells, drums, and {{ill|Charonia tritonis|ja|ほら貝|lt=conch shells|Charonia tritonis=Charonia tritonis|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and performances of Sumiyoshi Odori, in which children dressed as monks dance around a large umbrella held by a leader chanting songs. The dances and rituals aim to honor and enhance the spiritual power of the rice.
On {{ill|February 3, 1979|ja|1979th year 2月3日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Sumiyoshi no Otaue was designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. == See Also == * {{ill|Theatre of Japan|lt=Traditional performing arts of Japan|ja|伝統芸能|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
